  "transcript": [
    {
      "id": "line-000",
      "start": 0.0,
      "end": 11.32,
      "text": "This is a LibraVox recording. All LibraVox recordings are in the public domain. For more information or to volunteer, please visit LibraVox.org.",
      "note": ""
    },
    {
      "id": "line-001",
      "start": 12.02,
      "end": 20.96,
      "text": "Recorded by Kim Stone of Pirling on the Dark Side in Denver, Colorado, USA. ESOP's Fables, The Blind Man and the Cub.",
      "note": ""
    },
    {
      "id": "line-002",
      "start": 21.6,
      "end": 31.12,
      "text": "There once was a blind man who had so fine a sense of touch that when any animal was put into his hands, he could tell what it was by merely the feel of it.",
      "note": ""
    },
    {
      "id": "line-003",
      "start": 31.8,
      "end": 39.36,
      "text": "One day the cub of a wolf was put into his hands and he was asked what it was. He felt it for some time and then said,",
      "note": ""
    },
    {
      "id": "line-004",
      "start": 40.66,
      "end": 48.9,
      "text": "I am not sure whether it is a wolf's cub or a fox's, but this I know. It would never do to trust it in a sheepfold.",
      "note": ""
    },
    {
      "id": "line-005",
      "start": 49.66,
      "end": 54.7,
      "text": "Evil tendencies are early shown. End of The Blind Man and the Cub.",
      "note": ""
    }
  ],
